  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you repair the sole of a shoe?",
  "response": "Repairing the sole of a shoe can be done in several ways, depending on the type of damage and the materials of the shoe. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide for common repairs:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Assess the Damage**\n- Inspect the sole for cracks, holes, or worn-out areas.\n- Determine whether the sole is rubber, leather, or synthetic.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Clean the Sole**\n- Use a brush and soapy water to clean the sole thoroughly.\n- Let it dry completely before proceeding.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Repair a Worn-Out Sole**\n#### **Option A: Use Shoe Goo or Strong Adhesive**\n1. Fill in gaps or cracks with Shoe Goo or a similar heavy-duty adhesive.\n2. Smooth it out with a putty knife or spatula.\n3. Let it dry for 24 hours.\n\n#### **Option B: Patch the Sole**\n1. Cut a piece of rubber or leather to match the damaged area.\n2. Apply strong adhesive (e.g., contact cement) to both the patch and the sole.\n3. Press the patch firmly onto the sole and let it dry for 24 hours.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Fix a Loose Sole**\n1. Clean the area where the sole is separating from the shoe.\n2. Apply shoe adhesive (e.g., Barge Cement) to both surfaces.\n3. Press the sole back onto the shoe and clamp it in place (use rubber bands or weights if no clamp is available).\n4. Let it dry for 24 hours.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Replace the Sole (Advanced)**\n1. Remove the old sole carefully.\n2. Trace the shape of the shoe onto a new sole material (rubber or leather).\n3. Cut out the new sole and attach it using shoe adhesive or by sewing (for leather soles).\n4. Let it dry and trim any excess material.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Seal and Protect**\n- Apply a rubber or leather conditioner to protect the sole from future wear.\n- For rubber soles, consider adding a layer of shoe sealer for extra durability.\n\n---\n\n### **Tools and Materials Needed**\n- Shoe Goo or heavy-duty adhesive\n- Rubber or leather patch (if needed)\n- Clamps or rubber bands\n- Putty knife or spatula\n- Scissors or utility knife\n- Brush and soapy water\n\nIf the damage is extensive or the shoe is expensive, it\u2019s often best to take it to a professional cobbler for repair.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
